 areas of the city. He shows not only that postwar building was the result of conscious public policy but goes further, arguing that our cities reflect deep-seated insecurities and cultural malaise in surprisingly direct ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCity planningxCanada. 0aCity planningxOntarioxToronto. 0aCity planningxUnited States. 0aCity planningzCanada. 0aCity planningzOntariozToronto. 0aCity planningzUnited States. 0aUrbanismexCanada. 0aUrbanismexOntarioxTorontoxCanadaxOntarioxTorontoxUnited States. 0aUrbanismexÉtats-Unis. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356279040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773562790423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773562790/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles